␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀# Directory structure

UNIX platforms have a very specific directory structure, its root directories
discriminating between fundamental roles for files in them. For example, /lib is
for libraries, /bin is for binaries.

In Forth, every word defined by a unit is potentially usable interactively,
which makes the whole /lib vs. /bin distinction rather moot. Everything is
executable.

Because the breadth of applications included directly in Dusk OS is rather small
and that "user files" will typically be on a separate volume, we give ourselves
a wide root directory structure based on general topics of the included code.

/ar    Archive access
/asm   Assemblers
/bin   Binary blobs processing
/com   Communicate
/comp  Compilers
/cos   Collapse OS (see doc/cos/intro)
/doc   Documentation
/drv   Drivers
/emul  Emulators
/fs    Filesystems
/gr    Graphics
/home  Virgil's workspace
/lib   Miscellanous little routines
/sys   Subsystems
/tests Automated tests
/text  Text processing
/xcomp Cross compilation

## /ar -- Archive access

Provides decoding (and sometimes encoding) access to data structured in
particular manner. In this section fits:

* Compression and decompression
* tar
* Document formats such as MS Word and PDF

## /asm -- Assemblers

Provides assemblers for different CPUs or VMs. Those will convert mnemonics into
native bytecode.

Disassemblers also go there.

## /bin -- Binary blobs processing

Provides facilities to process binary blobs. Hex editors go there.

## /com -- Communicate

Provide facilities for communicating with other machines.

## /comp -- Compilers

Provides compilers for different languages such as DuskC. Those compilers will
typically use assemblers to yield native bytecode.

## /doc -- Documentation

Dusk documentation in text format.

## /drv -- Drivers

Drivers for supported peripherals. For each supported architecture, there's a
subdirectory. Drivers will be placed in the most general directory possible for
that peripheral.

## /emul -- Emulators

Provides facilities for emulating a machine. This includes CPU and peripheral
emulation logic.

## /fs -- Filesystems

Filesystem implementations, which run on top of storage drivers.

## /home -- Virgil's workspace

The contents of this directory is not really a part of Dusk because it
represents the "work" files that Dusk's main author uses when working within
Dusk. It's included in Dusk's packages because it's a good example of how Dusk
ought to be used effectively.

## /lib -- Miscellanous little routines

Each unit in this directory contain collections of little useful routines with
their usage sprinkled around the system.

## /pic -- Picture processing

Provides facilities to decode data representing pictures.

## /sys -- Subsystems

Subsystems are pieces of logic tied to a ressource, typically through a driver.

For example, the I/O subsystem sits on drivers providing "readbuf" and
"writebuf" to add a whole collection of useful routines on top of it.

## /tests -- Automated tests

Collection of tests for all units in the system. Its directory structure mirrors
the root structure. Each directory has a "all.fs" unit that includes all units
of the directory. Loading "/tests/all.fs" runs all tests in the system.

## /text -- Text processing

Provides facilities to process and vizualize textual data. Text editors go
there.

## /xcomp -- Cross compilation

Provides facilities to cross compile Dusk to any of the supported target
machines.
