Like in any Forth, Dusk's main mechanism for creating new words is ":".

  : foo bar baz ;

What this does is:

1. Create a new dictionary entry named "foo".
2. On some platforms, create a word mark [doc/hal].
3. Enter compile mode.
4. Compile calls to "bar", then "baz".
5. Call "exit," [doc/hal].
6. Stop compile mode.

There are other ways to create words differently. For example, "entry ( name
dict -- )" creates an entry in dictionary "dict" without creating a word mark or
entering compile mode. "code ( "name" -- )" creates a dictionary entry and a
word mark, but doesn't enter compile mode.

Those are relatively straightforward mechanisms. There are other ones that are a
bit more special, described below.

## Aliases

An alias is a shortcut to another word:

  alias noop myalias

Calling "myalias" is the same as calling "noop". An alias is a native jump to
its target, so there's almost no runtime overhead to using aliases.

You can change the target of an alias, you can use the word
"realias ( w tgt -- )" which makes target word "tgt" alias to word "w". Example:

  ' anotherword ' myalias realias

Note that while "tgt" is usually an alias, it doesn't have to be. You can make
a "hostile takeover" of a word with realias and brutally make it point
elsewhere. If you do, make sure that the word is big enough for a native jump.
For example, using realias on the word "noop", which only contains a "return"
op, would likely corrupt the dictionary entry of the following word.

Aliases have two main usages: dynamically pluggable words, or forward
declarations. For the latter type, there is also the syntactically more pleasant
word ":realias", which is a combination of, drum roll, ":" and "realias" and can
be used thus:

  alias abort foo \ Forward declaration
  : bar foo ;
  :realias foo bar ;

It is the equivalent of:

  alias abort foo \ Forward declaration
  : bar foo ;
  : _ bar ;
  current ' foo realias

except that further references to "foo" will link directly to the actual word
rather than going through the alias.

## Anonymous words with :~

Its a common pattern to define words that are used in very local context and
then never needed anymore. They can be called something like "_" to indicate
that their name don't matter and that they'll never be referenced anywhere.

This will, however, create a dictionary entry for "_". In addition to being a
bit wasteful, it's also an unwanted side effect in some cases, for example in
namespaces that represent a precise API. For example, operators in the C
compiler are defined in terms of namespaces and defining a "_" word in it
defines the "_" operator, something we don't want.

The ":~" and "~" words allow the definition and referencing of words without
creating dictionary entries:

  :~ 1+ . ;
  : print42 41 ~ ;

## :override

:override allows you to redefine a word while still using its previous behavior,
often to augment that behavior. Upon definition, the "~" pointer is updated to
provide the implementer with a way to reference the old word.

  : foo 1+ . ;
  42 foo \ prints 43
  :override foo 1+ ~ ;
  42 foo \ prints 44
